</blockquote>

<p>A particular shared daydream was that they were a married couple called Mr and Mrs John Barker, who lived above a shop.[18]</p>

<p>White recalled going to similar-sounding mixed parties to Smith from the age of five.Â  At one humiliating party, GÃ©rard kept his distance from her because her repurposed bridesmaidâ€™s dress of that year was an unfashionable yellow.Â  Her credibility was restored the following year, when she acquired an acceptable white and pink dress from another engagement as a bridesmaid.[19]</p>

<p>I could say much more about these sources but these were the main things that stood out to me.Â  I never realised such â€˜puppy loveâ€™ was allowed, let alone encouraged, in Edwardian times, and itâ€™s nice that both these only children had the opportunities to go to such parties.Â  Itâ€™s also interesting to see how family circumstances make so much difference - both ladies had very active imaginations, but Dodie Smith seemed to have benefitted from a livelier and more sociable home, and the title of her autobiography, <em>Look Back With Love</em>, suggests a really happy time in her life until her early teens, when her mother remarried and they moved to London.</p>

